Consider the following C program:
```
#include "seahorn/seahorn.h"
extern int unknown1();
extern int unknown2();
extern int unknown3();

/*
 * Adapted from ex17.c in NECLA test suite
 */

int main() {
   int flag = unknown1();
   int a = unknown2();
   int b = unknown3();
   int j = 0;

   for (b=0; b < 100 ; ++b){
      if (flag)
         j = j +1;
   }


   if(flag)
      sassert(j==100);
}

```
Output the loop invariants for the loop in the program above.
Let's think step by step.

invariants:
/*@ 
    loop invariant 0 <= b <= 100;
    loop invariant j == (b * (flag != 0));
*/

/*@ 
    loop invariant 0 <= b <= 100;
    loop invariant j == (flag ? b : 0);
*/

/*@ 
    loop invariant 0 <= b <= 100;
    loop invariant flag ? j == b : j == 0;
*/

/*@ 
    loop invariant 0 <= b <= 100;
    loop invariant j >= 0;
    loop invariant (flag != 0) ==> (j == b);
*/

